<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-determining-constants-in-nonlinear-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Determining Constants in Nonlinear Equations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine constants in nonlinear equations in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    20 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To use the properties of a straight line (gradient and intercept) to find unknown values in a non-linear model.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Facilitate the "Cracking the Code" activity. Provide groups with "straightened" graphs and challenge them to find the original constants. Encourage them to verify their found values by testing a point from the original data.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                A group of engineers found that the relationship between the pressure <m>P</m> and volume <m>V</m> of a gas follows the law <m>PV^k = C</m>. 
                They plotted a graph of <m>\log P</m> against <m>\log V</m> to "straighten" the data.
            </p>
            <p>
                The resulting straight line passes through the points <m>(1, 2.3)</m> and <m>(2, 0.9)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do:</alert>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Linearize the equation <m>PV^k = C</m> by taking logarithms on both sides.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Identify which part of your linear equation corresponds to the gradient (<m>m</m>) and which corresponds to the y-intercept (<m>c</m>).</p></li>
                    <li><p>Using the two points provided, calculate the gradient of the line. What is the value of <m>k</m>?</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find the y-intercept of the line. Use it to calculate the value of the constant <m>C</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Write down the final non-linear equation relating <m>P</m> and <m>V</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the procedure for calculating original constants from linear graph features.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> In the activity, students learned that the gradient of the straight line is often equal to the power (or its negative) in the original law, and the intercept is the log of the original coefficient. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The Mapping Rule:</alert> To find constants, always:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Calculate <m>m</m> from two points on the line.</li>
                            <li>Calculate <m>c</m> by substituting one point into <m>Y = mX + c</m>.</li>
                            <li>Equate <m>m</m> and <m>c</m> to their respective expressions in the linearized formula.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            Once a non-linear relationship has been converted to the linear form <m>Y = mX + c</m>, the original constants can be determined by mapping them to the gradient and y-intercept.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Common Mapping Scenarios:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For <m>y = ax^n \implies \log_{10} y = n\log_{10} x + \log_{10} a</m>:
                        <me>n = \text{gradient}</me>
                        <me>a = 10^{\text{intercept}}</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For <m>y = ab^x \implies \log_{10} y = (\log_{10} b)x + \log_{10} a</m>:
                        <me>b = 10^{\text{gradient}}</me>
                        <me>a = 10^{\text{intercept}}</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For <m>y = ax^2 + b</m>:
                        <me>a = \text{gradient}</me>
                        <me>b = \text{intercept}</me>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>How to determine constants in non-linear equations:</alert>
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li><p>Identify the linearized form of the equation.</p>
            <p>
                For example, if the original equation is <m>y = ax^n</m>, the linearized form is <m>\log y = n \log x + \log a</m>.
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Calculate the gradient and intercept from the straightened graph.</p>
            <p>
                For instance, if the line passes through <m>(X_1, Y_1)</m> and <m>(X_2, Y_2)</m>, the gradient is:
                <me>m = \frac{Y_2 - Y_1}{X_2 - X_1}</me>
                Then, using one point (e.g., <m>(X_1, Y_1)</m>) the intercept is:
                <me>Y_1 = mX_1 + c \implies c = Y_1 - mX_1</me>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>Map the gradient and intercept back to the original constants using the relationships established in the linearized form.</p>
            <p>
                For the example of <m>y = ax^n</m>, if the gradient is <m>m</m> and the intercept is <m>c</m>, then:
               <md>
                <mrow> n =\amp m </mrow>
                <mrow> a =\amp 10^c </mrow>
                <mrow> y = 10^c \times x^m </mrow>
               </md>
            </p></li>
        </ol>

    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are related by the equation <m>y = kx^n</m>. 
                When <m>\log y</m> is plotted against <m>\log x</m>, a straight line is obtained which passes through <m>(0.2, 0.7)</m> and <m>(0.5, 1.3)</m>. Find the values of <m>k</m> and <m>n</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Linearize: <m>\log y = n\log x + \log k</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the gradient (<m>n</m>):
                            <me>n = \frac{1.3 - 0.7}{0.5 - 0.2} = \frac{0.6}{0.3} = 2</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the y-intercept (<m>\log k</m>):
                            Substitute <m>n = 2</m> and the point <m>(0.2, 0.7)</m> into <m>Y = mX + c</m>:
                            <md>
                            <mrow>0.7 = 2(0.2) + \log k</mrow>
                            <mrow>0.7 = 0.4 + \log k</mrow>
                            <mrow>\log k = 0.3</mrow>
                            <mrow>k = 10^{0.3} = 2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                The values are <m>n = 2</m> and <m>k = 2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An experimental law is known to be <m>y = Ak^x</m>. A graph of <m>\log y</m> against <m>x</m> has a gradient of <m>-0.5</m> and passes through the point <m>(2, 4)</m>. Calculate <m>A</m> and <m>k</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                <p>
                    Linearize: <m>\log y = x \log k + \log A</m>.
                </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                <p>
                    The gradient is <m>\log k = -0.5</m>.
                </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                <p>
                    Find the intercept (<m>\log A</m>):
                    Substitute the gradient and point <m>(2, 4)</m> into <m>Y = mX + c</m>:
                    <md>
                    <mrow>4 = -0.5(2) + \log A</mrow>
                    <mrow>4 = -1 + \log A</mrow>
                    <mrow>\log A = 5</mrow>
                    <mrow>A = 10^5 = 100000</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                <p>
                    Find <m>k</m>:
                    <md>
                    <mrow>\log k = -0.5</mrow>
                    <mrow>k = 10^{-0.5} = 0.316</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            The values are <m>A = 100000</m> and <m>k = 0.316</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A straight line graph is obtained by plotting <m>\log y</m> against <m>\log x</m>. The line passes through <m>(1, 3)</m> and <m>(3, 7)</m>. If the relationship is <m>y = ax^n</m>, find <m>a</m> and <m>n</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <me>n = \frac{7 - 3}{3 - 1} = 2</me>
                    <me>3 = 2(1) + \log a \implies \log a = 1 \implies a = 10^1 = 10</me>
                    Result: <m>n=2, a=10</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The intensity <m>I</m> of light from a source at a distance <m>d</m> is given by <m>I = kd^n</m>. Data was plotted as <m>\log I</m> vs <m>\log d</m>, and the line has a gradient of <m>-2</m> and an intercept on the <m>\log I</m> axis of <m>1.5</m>. 
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Find the values of <m>k</m> and <m>n</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Calculate the intensity when the distance is 5 units.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>n =\amp -2</mrow>
                            <mrow>\log k =\amp 1.5 \implies k = 10^{1.5} = 31.62</mrow>
                        </md>
                       </p> 
                    </li> 
                    <li>
                        <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>I =\amp 31.62 \times (5)^{-2}</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp \frac{31.62}{25}</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp 1.265</mrow>
                        </md> 
                       </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> satisfy the equation <m>y^2 = ax + b</m>. A graph of <m>y^2</m> against <m>x</m> has a gradient of 3 and passes through <m>(4, 14)</m>. Find <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>a =\amp 3</mrow>
                        <mrow>14 =\amp 3(4) + b</mrow>
                        <mrow> b =\amp 2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Result: <m>a=3, b=2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> satisfy the equation <m>y = ax^2 + b</m>. A student plots <m>y</m> against <m>x^2</m> and obtains a straight line with gradient <m>3</m> passing through the point <m>(4,\ 15)</m>.
                    Find <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>Y = y</m> and <m>X = x^2</m>. The equation becomes <m>Y = aX + b</m>, so the gradient equals <m>a</m> and the y-intercept equals <m>b</m>.
                    <md>a = 3</md>
                    Substituting the point <m>(X, Y) = (4, 15)</m>:
                    <md>15 = 3(4) + b \implies b = 3</md>
                    Therefore <m>a = 3</m> and <m>b = 3</m>, giving <m>y = 3x^2 + 3</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are related by <m>y = ab^x</m>.
                    A graph of <m>\log y</m> against <m>x</m> gives a straight line with gradient <m>0.477</m> and y-intercept <m>0.301</m>.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Find the values of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Calculate <m>y</m> when <m>x = 5</m>.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Linearizing: <m>\log y = (\log b)\,x + \log a</m>. So:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\log b \amp= 0.477 \implies b = 10^{0.477} = 3</mrow>
                                <mrow>\log a \amp= 0.301 \implies a = 10^{0.301} = 2</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Therefore <m>a = 2</m> and <m>b = 3</m>, giving <m>y = 2 \times 3^x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>y = 2 \times 3^5 = 2 \times 243 = 486</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> satisfy the law <m>y = a + \dfrac{b}{x}</m>. When <m>y</m> is plotted against <m>\dfrac{1}{x}</m>, a straight line is obtained passing through the points <m>(0.125,\ 4)</m> and <m>(1,\ 11)</m>. Find <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let <m>Y = y</m> and <m>X = \dfrac{1}{x}</m>. The equation becomes <m>Y = bX + a</m>, so the gradient is <m>b</m> and the y-intercept is <m>a</m>.
                    <md>b = \frac{11 - 4}{1 - 0.125} = \frac{7}{0.875} = 8</md>
                    Using the point <m>(0.125, 4)</m>:
                    <md>4 = 8(0.125) + a \implies 4 = 1 + a \implies a = 3</md>
                    Therefore <m>a = 3</m> and <m>b = 8</m>, giving <m>y = 3 + \dfrac{8}{x}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student investigates the relationship between the length <m>L</m> (cm) of a pendulum and the period <m>T</m> (seconds) of its swing.
                </p>
                <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                    <row><cell><m>L</m> (cm)</cell><cell>25</cell><cell>50</cell><cell>75</cell><cell>100</cell></row>
                    <row><cell><m>T</m> (s)</cell><cell>1.00</cell><cell>1.41</cell><cell>1.73</cell><cell>2.00</cell></row>
                </tabular>
                <p>
                    The relationship is believed to follow <m>T^2 = kL</m>.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Construct a table of <m>T^2</m> against <m>L</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Plot <m>T^2</m> against <m>L</m> and draw the best straight line through the origin.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find the value of the constant <m>k</m> from your graph.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Use your equation to predict the period of a pendulum of length 150 cm.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                                <row><cell><m>L</m> (cm)</cell><cell>25</cell><cell>50</cell><cell>75</cell><cell>100</cell></row>
                                <row><cell><m>T^2</m> (s²)</cell><cell>1.00</cell><cell>1.99</cell><cell>2.99</cell><cell>4.00</cell></row>
                            </tabular>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>The points lie very close to a straight line through the origin.</p></li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the point <m>(100,\ 4.00)</m>:
                            <md>k = \frac{T^2}{L} = \frac{4.00}{100} = 0.04 \text{ s}^2\text{/cm}</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>T^2 = 0.04 \times 150 = 6 \implies T = \sqrt{6} \approx 2.45 \text{ s}</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A radioactive sample decays according to the law <m>N = N_0 e^{-\lambda t}</m>, where <m>N</m> is the number of atoms at time <m>t</m> (seconds). A graph of <m>\ln N</m> against <m>t</m> is a straight line with gradient <m>-0.03</m> and y-intercept <m>5.6</m>.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Find the values of <m>\lambda</m> and <m>N_0</m> (to 3 s.f.).</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find the number of atoms present after 40 seconds.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Linearizing: <m>\ln N = -\lambda t + \ln N_0</m>. Comparing:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\lambda \amp= 0.03</mrow>
                                <mrow>\ln N_0 \amp= 5.6 \implies N_0 = e^{5.6} \approx 270</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>N = 270\,e^{-0.03 \times 40} = 270\,e^{-1.2} \approx 270 \times 0.301 \approx 81 \text{ atoms}</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A scientist suspects the data below follows a power law <m>y = ax^n</m>. Complete the table of <m>\log x</m> and <m>\log y</m> values, plot <m>\log y</m> against <m>\log x</m>, and hence find <m>a</m> and <m>n</m>.
                </p>
                <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                    <row><cell><m>x</m></cell><cell>1</cell><cell>2</cell><cell>4</cell><cell>8</cell></row>
                    <row><cell><m>y</m></cell><cell>3</cell><cell>12</cell><cell>48</cell><cell>192</cell></row>
                    <row><cell><m>\log x</m></cell><cell>0</cell><cell>0.301</cell><cell>0.602</cell><cell>0.903</cell></row>
                    <row><cell><m>\log y</m></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
                </tabular>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Completed table:
                    <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                        <row><cell><m>\log x</m></cell><cell>0</cell><cell>0.301</cell><cell>0.602</cell><cell>0.903</cell></row>
                        <row><cell><m>\log y</m></cell><cell>0.477</cell><cell>1.079</cell><cell>1.681</cell><cell>2.283</cell></row>
                    </tabular>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The graph of <m>\log y</m> vs <m>\log x</m> is a straight line, confirming a power law.
                    <md>n = \frac{2.283 - 0.477}{0.903 - 0} = \frac{1.806}{0.903} = 2</md>
                    <md>\log a = 0.477 \implies a = 10^{0.477} = 3</md>
                    Therefore <m>y = 3x^2</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The intensity <m>P</m> of sound from a speaker is recorded at various distances <m>d</m> (metres). When <m>\log P</m> is plotted against <m>\log d</m>, the straight line passes through <m>(0,\ 2)</m> and <m>(1,\ 0)</m>.
                </p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Find the gradient and y-intercept of the line.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Write down the law relating <m>P</m> and <m>d</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Calculate the intensity at a distance of 5 metres.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{gradient} \amp= \frac{0 - 2}{1 - 0} = -2</mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{y-intercept} \amp= 2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From <m>\log P = -2\log d + 2</m>:
                            <md>n = -2, \quad \log a = 2 \implies a = 100</md>
                            Law: <m>P = 100d^{-2} = \dfrac{100}{d^2}</m> (the inverse square law of sound intensity).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>P = \frac{100}{5^2} = \frac{100}{25} = 4 \text{ units}</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Variables <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> are related by <m>s = ut + \tfrac{1}{2}at^2</m>. Dividing through by <m>t</m> gives
                    <md>\frac{s}{t} = u + \tfrac{1}{2}at</md>
                    so a plot of <m>\dfrac{s}{t}</m> against <m>t</m> is a straight line.
                </p>
                <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                    <row><cell><m>t</m> (s)</cell><cell>1</cell><cell>2</cell><cell>3</cell><cell>4</cell></row>
                    <row><cell><m>s</m> (m)</cell><cell>12</cell><cell>28</cell><cell>48</cell><cell>72</cell></row>
                </tabular>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Complete a table of <m>s/t</m> against <m>t</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Plot <m>s/t</m> against <m>t</m> and draw the best straight line.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Find <m>u</m> (the y-intercept) and <m>a</m> (twice the gradient) from your graph.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                                <row><cell><m>t</m></cell><cell>1</cell><cell>2</cell><cell>3</cell><cell>4</cell></row>
                                <row><cell><m>s/t</m></cell><cell>12</cell><cell>14</cell><cell>16</cell><cell>18</cell></row>
                            </tabular>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>The points are collinear.</p></li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Gradient <m>= \dfrac{18 - 12}{4 - 1} = 2 = \tfrac{1}{2}a</m>, so <m>a = 4 \text{ m/s}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            y-intercept: using point <m>(1, 12)</m>: <m>12 = u + 2(1) \implies u = 10 \text{ m/s}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Provide a "Constant Finder" worksheet with the mapping formulas already written out. Focus on linear forms where the intercept is directly equal to the constant (e.g., <m>y^2 = ax + b</m>).
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete the "Cracking the Code" activity and solve examples involving both power and exponential transformations.</line>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Present cases with unknown bases in exponents (e.g., <m>y = k a^x</m>) or multi-step rational laws like <m>y = \frac{x}{ax + b}</m> where the intercept must be carefully mapped.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

